ApolloOne reason Solomon is controversial at Goldman is that he is not a Go=
ldman lifer but got his start at Drexel Burnham Lambert, which was =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Campbell writes =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Crenowned for its rapacious=
 culture.=E2=80=9D Drexel disappeared in 1990, but it is still influential =
everywhere on Wall Street. Perhaps nowhere more so than at Apollo Global Ma=
nagement Inc., whose founders came from Drexel and which has perhaps the gr=
eatest continuity, culturally, with Drexel.  Here is a story about how Apol=
lo co-founder Josh Harris seems to be ceding power to another co-founder, M=
arc Rowan:While Harris still sits on meetings of the private equity investm=
ent committee and takes part in related discussions on strategy, dealmakers=
 are involving him less when arranging transactions, according to the peopl=
e. Since handing off control of the firm=E2=80=99s budget, his role in comp=
ensation decisions has diminished too, aside from weighing in on the most s=
ignificant questions, the people said.In recent months, Apollo took the ste=
p of updating his executive biography on its website, deleting a significan=
t line: Harris =E2=80=9Ctoday runs the day-to-day business of the firm.=E2=
=80=9DHow=E2=80=99s that going, culturally?Those amount to stark changes fo=
r Harris, 56, who for three decades has been known for working marathon hou=
rs and making his presence known throughout the New York-based private equi=
ty firm, running operations and pressing employees on the details of their =
deals. His decreased involvement has come with a sense of relief for some. =
When the topic arose recently, employees under Harris were heard humming th=
eir response: =E2=80=9CDing-Dong! The Witch is Dead=E2=80=9D from =E2=80=9C=
The Wizard of Oz.=E2=80=9DCharming!VoltswagenSure whatever:The United State=
s Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) is investigating Volkswagen=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9CVoltswagen=E2=80=9D debacle to see how the stunt affected =
the automaker=E2=80=99s stock price, and whether it broke any securities la=
ws, according to Der Spiegel.The faux rebranding took place on March 29th, =
when Volkswagen=E2=80=99s American subsidiary =E2=80=9Caccidentally=E2=80=
=9D published a draft press release about changing its name to Voltswagen i=
n a nod to the larger company=E2=80=99s push into electric vehicles. =E2=80=
=A6Volkswagen=E2=80=99s stock price increased as much as 12.5 percent at on=
e point, the equivalent of billions of dollars of market value. It=E2=80=99=
s unclear what the SEC is specifically interested in learning about, or wha=
t laws VW could have even broken in the first place.=C2=A0Yeah, I mean, the=
 law it broke is that you can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cmake any untrue statement =
of a material fact =E2=80=A6=C2=A0in connection with the purchase or sale o=
f any security.=E2=80=9D Volkswagen AG was not actually changing its name t=
o =E2=80=9CVoltswagen=E2=80=9D so the press release was untrue, the stock w=
ent up 12.5% so it was apparently material, and you will just have to trust=
 me that it was in connection with the purchase or sale of a security.[6]We=
, regrettably, have  talked about the =E2=80=9CVoltswagen=E2=80=9D early-Ap=
ril-Fools=E2=80=99 prank before. It came a couple of weeks after  this Bloo=
mberg News story claiming that Volkswagen=E2=80=99s chief executive officer=
 is trying to be more like Elon Musk, =E2=80=9Ctaking a hands-on role in ge=
tting VW=E2=80=99s message out on social media and staging splashy events b=
ig on ambition.=E2=80=9D I suppose if you were trying to do a painfully lit=
eral impression of Elon Musk, you might tweet some untrue stories about you=
r company and dare the SEC to come after you; that is very much  a thing th=
at Musk has done. But if you are really going to do the Musk impression, I =
think you have to tweet through it? Like Volkswagen should be on Twitter ri=
ght now tweeting obscenities about the SEC and promising never to respect i=
ts demands. You don=E2=80=99t get any Musk-imitation credit for going halfw=
ay!=C2=A0SPAC drug lawsuitI have nothing really to say about  this and don=
=E2=80=99t even entirely understand what is going on, but I do feel like I=
=E2=80=99m obligated to quote it here:A former CCUR Holdings Inc. sharehold=
er filed suit in Delaware against its board=E2=80=94including a brother of =
convicted junk bond scammer Gary Singer=E2=80=94claiming it wrongly wrote o=
ff insured funds seized in a drug bust when cashing out investors.The lawsu=
it, docketed Tuesday in Delaware Chancery Court, targets a 3,000-to-1 =E2=
=80=9Creverse stock split=E2=80=9D being undertaken by CCUR, a holding comp=
any that owns real estate and merchant cash advance operations, which holds=
 warrants to buy 8 million shares of Spartacus Acquisition Corp., a SPAC wi=
th $200 million behind it. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Anyone with fewer than 3,000 shar=
es got cashed out, the suit says. ...CCUR=E2=80=99s board allegedly dropped=
 the cash-out price even further, to $2.86 a share, following the arrest on=
 federal cocaine trafficking charges of Debra Lynn Mercer-Erwin, owner of W=
right Brothers Aircraft Title Inc., which was due to return $14 million in =
deposits to CCUR.But the seized funds were insured, and the board adjusted =
the price based on the unjustified assumption that the company won=E2=80=99=
t see its money again, according to the complaint.=C2=A0Setting aside the m=
echanics, and the question of insurance, it is not=C2=A0great=C2=A0when you=
 have to lower your merger price because your assets were seized in a drug =
bust (of someone else=E2=80=99s drug business, but still). You never really=
 see that in big-time public-company M&A, though I suppose it would violate=
 the =E2=80=9Ccompliance with law=E2=80=9D (and =E2=80=9Cno material advers=
e effect=E2=80=9D?) representations and possibly lead to a renegotiation of=
 the price there too.A new eraHere=E2=80=99s a story about how people who w=
ork in finance in New York would like to get back to ordinary life (seeing =
people in person, eating at restaurants), though=C2=A0without necessarily w=
anting to commute=C2=A0or put=C2=A0on pants. There=E2=80=99s gonna be an ad=
justment period:Another person who works at a hedge fund recalled having hi=
s first in-person professional meeting since the pandemic. He wore athletic=
 pants =E2=80=93 a =E2=80=9Cbusiness comfortable=E2=80=9D attire he is not =
eager to abandon."It was very casual and I went in Lulus," he said, referri=
ng to Lululemon-brand trousers.You=E2=80=99ve got maybe six months where yo=
u can show up to meetings in Lululemon and the other person can show up in =
a suit and you can both laugh and say =E2=80=9Clol pandemic=E2=80=9D and it=
=E2=80=99s a fun bonding moment. After that you=E2=80=99re just the weirdo =
showing up for work in sweatpants. Anyway I also really liked this:"After m=
ore than a year in isolation, I am prepared to have drinks with just about =
anyone who breathes," said Kai Liekefett, who defends corporations against =
hedge fund managers pushing for changes as co-chair of law firm Sidley Aust=
in's Shareholder Activism Practice."Even activists," he added.You know he=
=E2=80=99s been workshopping that but, fine, it's a good line. Also it=E2=
=80=99s probably true! I=E2=80=99d love to put on a suit and have a drink a=
t a nice bar with my mortal enemy right now. Besides the pants thing, there=
=E2=80=99s also going to be about a six-month period where just seeing peop=
le in person will be so exciting that everyone will forget=C2=A0to dislike =
each other. An activist will mount a proxy fight to try to get added to a c=
ompany=E2=80=99s board, and the board will be like =E2=80=9Cyou want to com=
e to board meetings? Come on in, welcome, we=E2=80=99d love to hang out wit=
h you, sure, you=E2=80=99re on the board.=E2=80=9D There will be a ton of m=
erger-and-acquisition=C2=A0activity=C2=A0just because CEOs will be so thril=
led to have dinner with each other that they=E2=80=99ll keep making deals.=
=C2=A0Things happenStocks Are Off to Best Start to a Presidential Term Sinc=
e Great Depression. Parametric fund earns =E2=80=98Gamma Hammer=E2=80=99 mo=
niker with bet on tranquil markets. Hertz Is Approved to Run Auction as Cha=
pter 11 Bidding War Enters Endgame. Credit Suisse  Risk Committee Head Exit=
s After Archegos Hit. Fried-Chicken Craze Is Causing U.S. to  Run Low on Po=
ultry.=C2=A0Goldman Sachs predicts quantum computing 5 years away from use =
in markets. Whoops, T-Pain Just Discovered Hundreds of Unread DMs. Let=E2=
=80=99s Stigmatize the Internet.=C2=A0Teen who moved into retirement commun=
ity by mistake shocks TikTok. =E2=80=9CI Found Some Noise in Cross-Section =
of Stock Returns.=E2=80=9D (Cf.)If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=
=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at th=
is link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg news=
letters here. Thanks![1] =E2=80=9CReasonable=E2=80=9D in the sense that pay=
ing $2.5 million for a big stake in, and effective control of, a shell comp=
any with a U.S. securities registration seems like it could be a sensible d=
eal for a certain sort of operator. Not in the sense that, like, the actual=
 money-losing deli is worth $8 million.[2] That number is maybe a bit exagg=
erated. The *new* shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the people who put in $2.5 mi=
llion the day before the warrants were issued =E2=80=94=C2=A0had warrants t=
o put in $50 million more. You might assume that they planned (and plan) to=
 do so.=C2=A0The existing shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0the high-school wrest=
ling coach who runs the deli, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0also have warrants to put=
 in another $106 million, but you might guess that they are less committed =
investors. I have no real idea though. I suppose the warrants are tradeable=
, and you might imagine that, if the merger is a good deal, someone will bu=
y the warrants from the earlier investors and pay $1 to exercise them.=C2=
=A0[3] I want to emphasize that (1) this is not the right way to think abou=
t SPAC warrants (which normally survive the merger and are bets on the cont=
inuing upside of the combined company, not a way to raise money to fund the=
 merger), (2) this is not the right way to think about warrants generally (=
which are options for the holders, not a reliable source of future cash for=
 the company), and (3) this is not really the right way to structure a capi=
tal call for a company that needs contingent future funding. (SPACs, for in=
stance, will sometimes go public with *forward purchase agreements* with th=
eir sponsors: That=E2=80=99s how you do the capital call, not giving the sp=
onsors warrants.) But from the context here, I am interpreting these warran=
ts as sort of a shaggy way to do a capital call.[4] Actually I probably pic=
ked it up in my previous job, at a law firm, which really is a partnership =
and so of course is run for the benefit of its partners. Goldman is (and ha=
s been since 1999) a public corporation that is owned by its shareholders, =
with a group of ersatz =E2=80=9Cpartners=E2=80=9D who are well-paid senior =
managers but not the actual owners of a partnership. But Goldman, when I wa=
s there from 2007 to 2011, definitely still cared about its heritage as a p=
artnership.[5] Hmm. In my time there, I would not have said Goldman was kno=
wn for =E2=80=9Cindividual talent.=E2=80=9D Historically Goldman had a cult=
ure of trying to prioritize anonymous interchangeable teams rather than ind=
ividual stars, of selling clients on Goldman rather than particular bankers=
, though of course it is hard to do that consistently. But there was, I thi=
nk, a culture of =E2=80=9Ccollective talent,=E2=80=9D if you will, an idea =
that what you get from hiring Goldman was not one special banker but *a lot=
* of special bankers. This is distinct from a culture of, like, =E2=80=9Cwh=
at you get from hiring Goldman is a corporation with a suite of technology =
products and a big balance sheet.=E2=80=9D To the extent the new Goldman is=
 M&A apps and online consumer banking, that does sort of de-emphasize the s=
pecial-human-relationships side of the firm.[6] Of course it wasn=E2=80=99t=
 *really*; Volkswagen was not trying to hype a stock offering by doing this=
 dumb name-change stunt. But as a matter of law, =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=98in c=
onnection with=E2=80=99=C2=A0element of Rule 10b-5 is satisfied if the alle=
ged misrepresentation or omission =E2=80=98is material to a decision by one=
 or more individuals (other than the fraudster) to buy or to sell=E2=80=99 =
a security, and thus Rule 10b-5 applies broadly to statements made to the s=
econdary market.=E2=80=9D In general the theory of =E2=80=9C everything is =
securities fraud=E2=80=9D requires a rule like that: A company can get in t=
rouble for securities fraud for making false statements that induce people =
to buy or sell its securities, even if *the company* isn=E2=80=99t selling =
or buying them.
